column58: Auxiliary Valve; Closure (e.g., Cap, Top, or Plug); Piping or Fittings
column168: ON 01-02-01 AT APPROXIMATELY 12:45PM, A FORT TRANSFER CO CARGO TANK WAS DISCOVERED LEAKING AT A DISCHARGE VALVE PACKING NUT, ON THE LEFT SIDE OF TRAILER, DURING A HAZMAT INSPECTION.  THE COMPANY WAS CONTACTED AND THEY ENTURN CONTACTED A CLEAN UP CREW.  THE LEAK WAS CAPTURED IN A PLASTIC BUCKET, AND AN ENVIRONMENTALLY FRIENDLY ABSORBANT WERE UTILIZED.

column58: Basic Material; Closure (e.g., Cap, Top, or Plug)
column62: Water Damage; Loose Closure, Component, or Device
column168: THE PACKAGE WAS UNLOADED WITH LEAKAGE NOTED ON THE BOX.  EXAMINATION OF THE INNER CONTAINER REVEALED THAT THE CONTAINER(S) HAD LOOSE CAP(S) AND LEAKED.  THE LEAKAGE WAS CONTAINED.  THE CAP(S) WERE SECURED.  THE CARTON WAS WET BUT OTHERWISE UNDAMAGED.  THE PACKAGE WAS REPACKED FOR RETURN TO SHIPPER.

A CREW WAS SWITCHING CARS, AND A CONDUCTOR NOTICED AS THIS CAR PASSED BY THAT IT WAS VENTING FROM THE TOP OF THE CAR.  THE YARDMASTER WAS NOTIFIED, THE CAR WAS PLACED IN A CLEAR TRACK AND THE RUPTURE DISC WAS REPLACED.

RESPONDED TO THE SPILL ON PD-6. FOLLOWED THE DECISION TREE FOR PROCESSING. PROCESSED FOLLOWING THE UPS DMP PROCEDURES. CONTAINED AND SOLIDIFIED MATERIAL. I WORE THE PROPER P.P.E. DROPPED PACKAGE CAUSED LEAKAGE. HUB MANAGER SHOULD REVIEW PACKAGE HANDLING RULES.

column42: PETROLEUM GASES, LIQUEFIED OR LIQUEFIED PETROLEUM GAS
column62: Abrasion; Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: ON 01/04/2001 AT 2000 HOURS THE DRIVER OF UNIT 5936, BOBTAIL PROPANE TRUCK, TAPPED THE BRAKES, THE WHEEL TURNED VIOLENTLY AND THE TRUCK WENT INTO A ROLL.  THERE WAS A SMALL RELEASE OF PROPANE )2-3 GALLONS) IN VAPOR FORM, WHILE DISSIPATED INTO THE ATMOSPHERE.  THERE WERE NO EVACUATIONS.  THE NORTH CAROLINA HWY PATROL AND BLUE RIDGE FIRE DEPARTMENT RESPONDED.  THE PROPANE TRUCK WAS MOVED FROM A RIDGE TO A LOWER LEVEL PORTION OF GREEN RIVER ROAD AND THE REMAINING PROPANE WAS PUMPED OFF.  8 TREES WERE DAMAGED IN THE ACCIDENT. GREEN RIVER ROAD WAS CLOSED 4 TO 5 HOURS.  DRIVER RICHARD PACK, WENT TO DOCTOR, WAS SORE FROM ACCIDENT, WENT BACK TO WORK 1-5-01.
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column168: PASCHALL ARRIVED AT CONSIGNEE TO DISCOVER SEVERAL BARRELS OF PRODUCT HAD OVERTURNED IN THE TRAILER AND 1 BARREL HAD ITS LID TO COME OFF AND ALLOW ALL 55 GALLONS OF THE PRODUCT TO LEAK ONTO THE TRAILER FLOOR.  CONSIGNEE REFUSED 40 BARRELS BECAUSE OF THE LEAK.  EMI WAS CALLED AND THEY SENT A LOCAL CONTRACTOR OUT TO HANDLE THE SPILL CLEAN-UP.  THE PRODUCT WAS OFF LOADED ONTO A DOCK AREA AND THE TRAILER WAS CLEANED OUT BY THE CLEAN-UP CREW AND THE PRODUCT RELOADED AND REPACKAGED FOR SHIPMENT BACK TO THE SHIPPER.  THE SHIPPER ALSO REQUESTED THAT THE MATERIAL THAT WAS CLEANED UP BE SENT BACK TO THEM ALSO.  THE SPILL WAS COMPLETED AND THE SHIPMENT RETURNED BACK TO THE SHIPPER.
THE 5 GAL PAIL WAS SET TO THE FLOOR AND SPLIT AT THE SEAM.  THE SPILL WAS CLEANED AND OVERPACKED.

column168: FREIGHT WAS LOADED ON TO THE PAILS CAUSING LEAK.  THE SPILL WAS CLEANED AND OVERPACKED.  SENT TO DESTINATION.

DRIVER IN ROUTE TO DELIVERY.  TOTE STARTED LEAKING IN TRANSIT.  DUE TO METAL CASE HOLDING TOTE.  METAL BENT IN CREATING HOLE IN TOTE BOTTOM.  TRI-STATE MANAGEMENT NOTIFIED AND LEAKAGE CONTAINED.  NO LEAKAGE FROM TRAILER DURING TRANSIT.  SPILL CLEANED & PROPERLY DISPOSED OF.  CONSIGNEE NOTIFIED AND WILL CONTACT SHIPPER OF PACKAGING PROBLEMS.  FREIGHT WAS NOT LOADED IMPROPERLY.

TRAILER AT CARRIER TERMINAL FOR DISPATCH. PRODUCT STARTED DRIPPING FROM THE BELLY SKIN OF TRAILER. MATERIALS CONTAINED IN A BUCKET & LOAD WAS TRANSFERRED TO ANOTHER TRAILER. STATE POLICE & STATE D.E.Q. WERE PRESENT FOR THE TRANSFER

column168: TWENTY-FOUR DRUMS TENDERED TO CC EASTERN ON SKIDS. PICK-UP DRIVER STRIPPED DOWN TWO SKIDS (8 DRUMS) FOR SAFER TRANSPORTATION. ALL DRUMS LOADED TO NOSE  OF TRAILER. DOCKMAN STRIPPED OFF OTHER FREIGHT TO DOCK AND OUTBOUND TRAILERS. DOCKMAN WAS ATTEMPTING TO RELOAD LOOSE DRUMS ONTO SKID. WHILE ROLLING DRUM ONTO SKIDS, DRUM CAUGHT FORK AND PUNCTURED. DOCKMAN LEFT DRUM IN UPRIGHT POSITION UNABLE TO CONTAIN SPILL DUE TO FUMES. ALL DOCK PERSONEL WERE EVACUATED FROM DOCK AREA. EMERGENCY RESPONSE CLEAN-UP CREW WERE CALLED IN. CREW ARRIVED AT 2200 HOURS. SPILL WAS CLEANED UP AT 2400 HOURS.

column168: DRESSED IN FULL P.P.E. I WAS CALLED TO RESPOND TO A LEAKING PARCEL AT DOOR #1.  I FOUND A BOX, LABELED WITH A DOT DIAMOND LABEL (FLAMMABLE LIQUID) AND 5 PART DOT SHIPPING PAPER,WITH A DARK BLACK STAIN UPON THE TOP.  I CONSULTED THE DECISION TREE AND FOLLOWED IT TO THE FLAMMABLE LIQUID RESPONSE SHEET.  THE CONTAMINATED WASTE WAS DISPOSED OF VIA THE DNP PROCESS.  THE UNCONTAMINATED ITEMS WERE RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER IN A SALVAGE DRUM.  I DECONTAMINATED MY P.P.E.
THE FREIGHT WAS DAMAGED BY SHIFTING FREIGHT, THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED IN PACKAGE AND THE FREIGHT WAS OVERPACKED AND SENT TO DESTINATION.

WHEN REWORKING A CITY ROUTE TRAILER TO MAKE IT MORE CONVENIENT TO DELIVER THE FREIGHT, THE OPERATOR OF THE FORKLIFT ACCIDENTALLY PUNCHED A HOLE INTO A 55 GALLON DRUM OF ISOPROPANOL CAUSING THE ENTIRE CONTENTS TO LEAK OUT.  CONSOLIDATED FREIGHTWAYS PERSONNEL CLEANED ALL OF THE SPILLED MATERIAL UTILIZING ABSORBENT.  ALL SPILLED MATERIAL WAS CLEANED UP AND PLACED INTO DRUMS FOR DISPOSAL. ALL FORKLIFT OPERATORS NEEDED TO BE CAREFUL WHETHER LOADING OR UNLOADING FREIGHT.  THERE WAS NO PERSONNEL AFFECTED BY THE SPILLED PRODUCT.

TWO BOXES WERE CRUSHED WHEN OTHER FREIGHT SHIFTED DURING TRANSIT. THE SPILLAGE WAS NEUTRALIZED WITH AMPHOMAG AND DISPOSED OF PROPERLY. THE BOXES WERE RECOUPED INTO DOT APPROVED SALVAGE DRUMS WITH CHEMICAL LINERS, PROPERLY MARKED AND LABELED.  THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED FOR DISPOSITION.

WHILE UNLOADING, SEVEN BAGS WERE DISCOVERED LEAKING.  THE SHIPMENT WAS RECOUPED INTO A CHEMICAL LINED, PROPERLY MARKED AND LABELED OVERPACK.  THE SPILLAGE WAS SWEPT UP AND PLACED IN THE OVERPACK. THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED.
WHILE LOADING, ONE CYLINDER WAS DAMAGED BY A FORKLIFT BLADE.  THE CYLINDER WAS ALLOWED TO VENT OUT.  THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED AND WILL RECEIVED THE CYLINDER BACK.

WHILE SITTING IN THE YARD AWAITING TRANSPORT TO THE RAILYARD, A LOADED TRAILER WAS DISCOVERED TO BE LEAKING.  THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PLACED BOOMS AROUND THE AREA TO CONTAIN THE FREE PRODUCT.  THE TRAILER WAS THEN BROUGHT BACK TO THE DOCK AND STRIPPED.  WHILE STRIPPING THE TRAILER, THREE WET CARTONS, EACH CONTAINING FOUR, ONE GALLON GLASS BOTTLES WERE DISCOVERED IN THE NOSE OF THE TRAILER. FURTHER INVESTIGATION DETERMINED THAT EIGHT BOTTLES WERE DAMAGED AND FOUR WERE UNAFFECTED.  APPROXIMATELY EIGHT GALLONS OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED.  A PORTION OF THE FREE PRODUCT WAS ABSORBED BY THE CARTONS AND THE REST EVAPORATED.  APPARENTLY THE DAMAGE TO THE BOTTLES WAS DUE TO A PUNCTURE BY ADJACENT FREIGHT.  THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM USED LEVEL C PPE TO PERFORM THE CLEANUP.  THE PPE, THREE WET CARTONS, AND EIGHT DAMAGED BOTTLES WERE PLACED INTO A 55 GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM.  THE RECOVERY DRUM WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION.  THE FOUR UNAFFECTED BOTTLES WERE RECOUPED AND ARE BEING HELD AT THE TERMINAL, ALONG WITH THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT, PENDING FURTHER INVESTIGATION. NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED.  THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

THE OVERPACK DRUM WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL PENDING SHIPPER CONTACT.  THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT WILL CONTINUE ON TO THE CONSIGNEE.  NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED.  THE MSDS WAS RECEIVED FROM THE SHIPPER.

WHILE UNLOADING, TWO WET CARTONS, EACH CONTAINING TWO, 1/2 PINT CONTAINERS, WERE DISCOVERED IN THE MIDDLE OF THE TRAILER.  UPON FURTHER INVESTIGATION, IT WAS DETERMINED THAT ALL FOUR CONTAINERS WERE DAMAGED.  APPROXIMATELY ONE PINT OF FREE PRODUCT WAS RELEASED. APPARENTLY THE RELEASE WAS DUE TO A PUNCTURE DURING LOADING.  THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEAN-UP USING LEVEL C PROTECTION AND ABSORBENT NEUTRALIZER.  THE CLEAN-UP MATERIALS, DAMAGED CARDBOARD, AND THE FOUR DAMAGED CONTAINERS WERE PLACED INTO A 10-GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM WHICH WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL FOR DISPOSITION.  THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT WILL BE FORWARDED TO THE CONSIGNEE.  THERE WERE NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES REPORTED.  THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

WHILE UNLOADING, ONE DAMAGED 55 GALLON STEEL DRUM WAS DISCOVERED IN THE TRAILER.  APPROXIMATELY 2 GALLONS OF FREEPRODUCT WERE RELEASED. APPARENTLY THE DRUM WAS CRUSHED IN TRANSIT BY HEAVY TOPFREIGHT.  THE TERMINAL HAZ-MAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEAN UP USING LEVEL C PROTECTION AND ABSORBENT MATERIALS.  THE CLEAN UP MATERIALS WERE PLACED INTO A 55 GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM WHICH WILL BE HELD FOR DISPOSITION AT THE TERMINAL.  THE DAMAGED DRUM WAS PLACED INTO AN 85 GALLON POLY OVERPACK DRUM AND HELD PENDING SHIPPER CONTACT.  THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT CONTINUED ON TO THE CONSIGNEE.  NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED.  THE MSDS WAS RECEIVED FROM THE SHIPPER.

column42: HYPOCHLORITE SOLUTIONS WITH 16 PERCENT OR MORE AVAILABLE CHLORINE
column168: THIS SPILL OCCURRED DURING THE MORNING PACKAGE SORT OPERATION AT THE RIVA FEDEX STATION.  WHEN THE SPILL CLEANUP SPECIALIST OPENED THE BOX TO INVESTIGATE THE INNER CONTAINERS DURING HIS SPILL CLEANUP, THE PACKAGE WAS FOUND TO CONTAIN THE 3 INNER BOTTLES OF BLEACH/SODIUM HYPOCHLORITE AND 3 AEROSOL CANS OF A TUB/TILE CLEANER.  AFTER THE SPILL WAS CLEANED UP PER FEDEX POLICY, THE SHIPPER WAS CONTACTED FOR AN MSDS.  SINCE THE BLEACH WAS 5.25% CONCENTRATION AND THERE WERE AEROSOL CANS IN THE PACKAGE THE FAA WAS NOTIFIED ABOUT THIS HIDDEN DANGEROUS GOODS SHIPMENT.  ANOTHER PACKAGE IN THIS 7 PIECE SHIPMENT LEAKED A PINE SCENTED CLEANER AND WAS HELD WITH THIS PIECE AT THE RIVA STATION.  THE OTHER 5 PIECES WERE DELIVERED TO THE CONSIGNEE ON THE SATURDAY PRIOR TO THIS SPILL ON MONDAY SINCE THEY WERE SATURDAY DELIVERY SERVICE PACKAGES.  THIS SHIPMENT WILL BE HELD AT THE RIVA STATION PENDING AN INVESTIGATION BY THE AUTHORITIES WITH THE FAA OR THE FEDERAL HIGHWAY ADMINISTRATION(THIS WAS AN INTRASTATE SHIPMENT).

column42: VEHICLE, FLAMMABLE GAS POWERED OR VEHICLE, FUEL CELL, FLAMMABLE GAS POWERED
column168: THE PACKAGE WAS STOPPED AT OUR DENVER RAMP BECAUSE OF ODOR AND THE BOTTOM OF THE BOX WAS STARTING TO FALL APART.  UPON OPENING THE PACKAGE WE FOUND A GENERATOR.  THE GAS TANK APPEARED TO HAVE BEEN EMPTY BUT THERE WAS PAPER INSIDE THE BOX USED FOR CUSHIONING THAT WAS SOAKED WITH WHAT APPEARED TO BE SOME TYPE OF FUEL.  EVIDENTLY THERE WAS STILL SOME LIQUID IN THE FUEL LINES THAT CAME OUT IN THE PACKAGE.  THE FAA WAS CONTACTED AS WAS THE SHIPPER. THE PACKAGE IS HELD PENDING INVESTIGATION.

THE RAILCAR WAS BEING LOADED AT THE FACILITY. THE LOADER OBSERVED THE OVERFILL THROUGH THE REMOTE CAMERA AND IMMEDIATELY CLOSED THE LOAD VALVES.  THE MATERIAL WAS CONTAINED, PUMPED INTO A WASTE TANK, AND WAS RECYCLED THROUGH THE WASTE WATER PROCESS.  INVESTIGATION INDICATES THAT THE RAILCAR WAS NOT EMPTY BEFORE LOADING. ACTION ITEMS FROM THIS INCIDENT ARE TO CONSIDER OVERFILL PROTECTION FOR RAILCARS AND DEVELOPING A PROCEDURE TO ACCURATELY ACCOUNT FOR HEEL VOLUMES.

column42: NITRIC ACID OTHER THAN RED FUMING, WITH AT LEAST 65 PERCENT, BUT NOT MORE THAN 70 PERCENT NITRIC ACID
column168: DURING NITRIC TANK CAR UNLOADING (AFTER 33MIN. FROM WHEN ACID FLOW STARTED) THE QUICK CLEAN VALVE DISCONNECTED CAUSING A SPILL OF NITRIC ACID. UPON NOTICING THE LEAK, AN EMPLOYEE SHUT OFF THE FLOW USING ONE OF THE PNEUMATIC CUT OFF VALVES. THE SPILL WAS APPROXIMATELY 100 GALLONS AND WAS CONTAINED WITHIN THE TANKER UNLOADING AREA. THE ACID WAS PUMPED INTO THE DILUTE ACID TANK ALONG WITH WATER USED IN THE CLEAN UP. THE AREA WAS CLEANED AND DECONTAMINATED. SEE ATTACHED PAPERWORK EXPLAINING ACTION TAKEN TO PREVENT FURTHER OR FUTURE INCIDENTS. FOLLOWING THE UNLOADING SPILL INCIDENT THAT OCCURRED WITH OUT TANK WAGON (SERIAL #35263) AT THE MITSUBISHI PLANT IN THEODORE, ALABAMA, ON JANUARY 10, 2001, ASHLAND SPECIALTY CHEMICAL COMPANY IN PUEBLO, COLORADO, TOOK THE FOLLOWING MEASURES TO PREVENT SIMILAR INCIDENTS IN THE FUTURE. EXAMINED THE POINT OF THE EQUIPMENT FAILURE (THE QUICK CLEAN VALVE) USING PHOTOGRAPHS TAKEN AT THE SCENE AT THE SCENE OF THE INCIDENT. THESE PHOTOS WERE COMPARED TO THE EQUIPMENT SETUP ON AN IDENTICAL TANK WAGON. THE TANK WAGON EQUIPMENT APPEARED TO BE IN PROPER ORIENTATION, AND THERE WAS NO DOCUMENTATION OF A CHANGE TO THE QUICK CLEAN VALVE OCCURRING AT THE PUEBLO FACILITY. MADE AN INQUIRY TO MITSUBISHI ASKING WEATHER THEY HAD PERFORMED MAINTENANCE TO THEIR EQUIPMENT. MITSUBISHI AFFIRMED THAT THEY HAD CHANGED THEIR UNLOADING HOSE IN SEPTEMBER. AFTER DETAILED DISCUSSION WITH MITSUBISHI CONCERNING THE CHANGE THAT HAD BEEN MADE, ASHLAND PURCHASED REPLACEMENT EQUIPMENT AS A GOODWILL GESTURE AND TRAVELED TO THE MITSUBISHI FACILITY TO ASSIST WITH THE REPAIRS. ASHLAND EXAMINED THE MITSUBISHI EQUIPMENT UPON ARRIVAL AND FOUND THAT THEIR UNLOADING HOSE HAD BEEN IMPROPERLY REASSEMBLED. ASHLAND PROVIDED TECHNICAL ASSISTANCE IN COMPLETING THE REPAIRS AND ALSO PROVIDED TRAINING IN THE PROPER TECHNIQUES FOR TANK WAGON UNLOADING. ASHLAND OBSERVED WHILE A MITSUBISHI EMPLOYEE CONNECTED AND UNLOADED A TANK WAGON TO CONFIRM THAT THE TRAINING WAS UNDERSTOOD.

column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: DRIVER DEPARTED PLANT AT 5:45 AM ON 1-8-01 TO MAKE A DELIVERY TO SOUTHERN ENERGY IN KING GEORGE, VA. HE WAS ON PINNER ST. AT THE INTERSECTION OF PINNER AND HIGHLAND WHEN MOMENTARILY BLINDED BY THE BRIGHT LIGHTS OF AN ONCOMING CAR, CAUSING DRIVER TO MISJUDGE THE CURVE, WHEN CORRECTION THE TRK., LIQUID IN THE TANKER CAUSED TRUCK & TRAILER TO ROLL OVER ON PASSENGERS SIDE. LOAD WAS CONTAINED BY TANK EXCEPT FOR A SMALL LEAK ON A FLANGE ON BOTTOM OF PUMP. LEAK WAS ISOLATED FROM TANK BY THE INTERNAL VALVE. DRIVER WAS TAKEN TO THE EMERGENCY ROOM & RELEASED WITH ONLY MINOR BUMPS & BRUISES, TANK & TRAILER WAS UPRIGHTED. TRAILER WAS TAKEN BACK TO THE PLANT TO BE UNLOADED & EVACUATED AND TRACTOR TAKEN TO SHOP.

column168: DRIVER WAS APPROACHING INTERSECTION OF HIGHWAY 157 AND HIGHWAY 36.  HE WAS TRAVELING SOUTH ON HIGHWAY 157.  AS HE APPROACHED THE INTERSECTION, A CAR STARTED TO PULL OUT A GRAVEL PARKING LOT ON THE RIGHT SIDE OF THE ROAD. THE CAR STOPPED BEFORE PULLING OUT ONTO THE HIGHWAY.  AFTER STARTING, THE CAR PULLED DIRECTLY INTO THE PATH OF OUR UNIT AND STOPPED IN THE SOUTHBOUND LANE.  THE DRIVER OF OUR UNIT SWERVED TO THE LEFT, GOING INTO THE NORTHBOUND LANE TO AVOID HITTING THE DRIVER'S SIDE OF THE VEHICLE.  THE DRIVER THEN HAD TO IMMEDIATLEY SWERVE BACK TO THE RIGHT TO AVOID A HEAD ON COLLISION WITH THE NORTHBOUND TRAFFIC.  WHEN HE SWERVED BACK, IT CAUSED THE PRODUCT TO SHIFT, CAUSING THE TRACTOR AND TRAILER TO ROLL ONTO ITS RIGHT SIDE, SKIDDING ACROSS THE PAVEMENT AND ROLLING OFF OF THE HIGHWAY ONTO AN EMBANKMENT AND COMING TO REST.  IN ORDER TO GET THE TRAILER AND TRACTOR UPRIGHT, THE PRODUCT HAD TO BE TRANSFERRED INTO ANOTHER TRAILER.  DURING THE UNLOADING, THE TRAILER HAD TO BE PRESSURIZED, CAUSING THE PRODUCT TO LEAK FROM THE RELIEF VALVE.

OVERFLOWED A TANK TRUCK AFTER AN ELECTRONIC HIGH LEVEL ALARM DID NOT GO OFF AND ALERT THE LOADERS TO SHUT THE PROCESS OFF AT THE APPROPRIATE TIME. THIS PROCESS HAS BEEN REDESIGNED TO USE A MANUAL GAUGING STICK INSTEAD OF THE HIGH LEVEL ALARM.  THIS ALLOWS A MORE ACTIVE PARTICIPATION OF THE LOADER IN THE PROCESS.

AFTER UNLOADING THE TRAILER.  THE DRIVER WAS IN THE PROCESS OF DISCONNECTING THE PRODUCT HOSE FROM THE PUMP.  THE DRIVE FAILED TO BLEED THE PRESSURE FROM THE HOSE AS HE RELEASED THE EAR ON THE PRODUCT HOSE FUEL SPRAYED INTO HIS FACE AND RIGHT EYE. HE HAD HIS BUCKET UNDER THE PUMP CATCHING THE PRODUCT IN IT. HE DRAINED HIS HOSE INTO THE BUCKET ALSO AFTER COMPLETING THE DISCONNECTING.  HE DUMPED THE RESIDUE BACK INTO OUR TANK APP. 2GALS. THERE WAS NO PRODUCT SPILLED ON THE SURFACE.
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column168: APPROX. 10 GALLONS OF PRODUCT SPILT DUE TO DRIVER INATTENTIVENESS  THE DRIVER AFTER UNLOADING DISCONNECTED HOSE FILL W/PRODUCT RESULTING IN SPILLAGE.  SPILL CONTAINED IN CONTAINMENT AREA FILLED W/GRAVEL.

APPROX. 15 GALLON SPILL OCCURRED DUE TO UNLOADING VALUE EQUIPMENT DAMAGE FROM VEHICLE ACCIDENT.  PLEASE SEE POLICE REPORT FOR FULL ACCOUNT.  NOTE: POLICE REPORT STATES PRODUCT IS NUMBER 1203 GASOLINE; ACTUAL PRODUCT ID AND CHEMICAL TRADE IS NA1993 DIESEL FUEL. ON NUMBER 23 SECTIONS B AND C THIS IS NOT PRODUCT LOST DAMAGES-DUE TO COLLISION.

column168: SPILL - OVERFILL DUE TO INCORRECT STICK READINGS. PRODUCT CONTAINED AND CLEANED UP.  DAMAGE TO ASPHALT.  ASPHALT HAS BEEN REPAIRED.
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column42: GASOHOL GASOLINE MIXED WITH ETHYL ALCOHOL, WITH NOT MORE THAN 10% ALCOHOL
column168: SPILL DUE TO OVERFILL INTO VR SYSTEM.  SPILLED APPROXIMATELY 250 GALLONS DRIVER GIVEN WRONG TANK CHART INFORMATION AND USED THE WRONG VR FITTING. AUTHORITIES CALLED TO CLEAN UP SPILL.
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column42: GASOHOL GASOLINE MIXED WITH ETHYL ALCOHOL, WITH NOT MORE THAN 10% ALCOHOL
column168: SPILL CAUSED BY A DEFECTIVE VENT (VR) SYSTEM AT STATION.  CAUSED TANK TO OVERPRESSURE AND PRODUCT SPILLED OUT OF A REMOTE STICK HOLE. A DEFECTIVE CAP WAS ON THE STICK HOLE.  IF STATION HAD A PROPER CAP OVER HOLE THIS SPILL WOULD NOT HAVE HAPPENED.  MILLER OIL WAS NOTIFIED THAT THEY NEED THEIR MAINTENANCE DEPARTMENT TO REPLACE GASKET ON CAP AT REMOTE STICK HOLE AND CLEAN THE CAP TO MAKE SURE IT FITS PROPERLY. AUTHORITIES WERE CALLED TO CLEAN UP SPILL.
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column168: PACKAGE HAD LOOSE CAPS, I PROCEEDED TO PROCESS AND DISPOSE OF PACKAGE FOLLOWING HAZARDOUS MATERIAL DISPOSAL PROCEDURES.  THE SHIPPER NEEDS TO MAKE SURE THE CAPS ARE ON RIGHT.

UNIT STOPPED FOR A BREAK WHEN DRIVER NOTICED SUBSTANCE LEAKING FROM THE TRAILER CHEMTREC NOTIFIED ALONG WITH SHIPPER FERGUSON HARBOUR INC WAS CONTRACTED TO CONTAIN AND CLEAN THE SPILL UP.  IT WAS FOUND THAT A PIN HOLE AT THE BOTTOM OF DRUM WAS THE CAUSE OF THE LEAK UNDETERMINED AS TO WHAT CAUSED THE PIN HOLE IN DRUM.  FERGUSON HARBOUR PLACED THE LEAKING DRUM IN AN OVERPACK.  FERGUSON HARBOUR NEUTRALIZED THE SPILL WITH SODA ASH.

column42: GASOLINE INCLUDES GASOLINE MIXED WITH ETHYL ALCOHOL, WITH NOT MORE THAN 10% ALCOHOL
column168: DRIVER OVERFILLED 2000 ABOVEGROUND GASOLINE TANK, SPILLING 25 GALLONS. DRIVER NOT IN ATTENDANCE AT FUELING POINT WHEN NOZZLE BECAME DISENGAGED FROM TANK FILL PIPE.  THERE WERE NO EQUIPMENT OR TANK PROBLEMS ASSOCIATED WITH THIS SPILL.  CLEANUP HAS BEEN COMPLETED.

column42: GASOLINE INCLUDES GASOLINE MIXED WITH ETHYL ALCOHOL, WITH NOT MORE THAN 10% ALCOHOL
column168: WHILE WEARING FULL PEE, I RESPONDED TO A WET PACKAGE AT DOOR 13.  I THEN FOLLOWED THE DECISION TREE AND THE STEPS FOR THE FLAMMABLE LIQUID RESPONSE SHEET.  PACKAGE CONTAINED INTO TUB AND WAS PROCESSED THROUGH THE DMP AREA.                    WCG

THE DRIVER WAS LOADING MOLTEN SULFUR IN A MULTI-COMPARTMENT SULFUR TANK.  THE EQUALIZER PIPE THAT CONNECTS THE TANKS WAS BLOCKED BY HARDENED SULFUR RESIDUE RESULTING IN AN OVERFLOW OF THE REAR COMPARTMENT.
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column168: DRIVER UNLOADING ACETONE DISCOVERED THE GASKET LEAKING FROM THE HOSE CONNECTION AT THE EXTERNAL VALVE.  DRIVER SHUT DOWN THE UNLOADING PROCESS AND REPLACED THE GASKET AND FINISHED THE UNLOADING PROCESS. ABOUT 1/2 GAL. LEAKED PLANT EMPLOYEE USED ABSORBENT MATERIAL TO CLEAN UP SPILL.
PRODUCT WAS DRIPPING FROM TOP OF CUSTOMER TANK.  CUSTOMER FULL LINE WAS LEAKING.  USED SPILL PADS TO CLEAN UP.
BOX FOUND OF BELT WET.  SO HAZMAT RESPONDER AND PROCESSED THROUGH DMP.

DRIVER BEGAN LOADING CRUDE OIL FROM A 1000 BBL. TANK, AFTER ASSURING HIMSELF THAT LOADING WAS PROCEEDING PROPERLY.  HE LEFT REAR OF TRAILER AND ENTERED CAB OF TRUCK.  AFTER PREPARING PAPERWORK, THE DRIVER FELL ASLEEP. WHEN HE AWOKE HE REALIZED THAT OIL WAS OVERFLOWING, STOPPED TRUCK PUMP THEN CLOSED VALVES.  HE TRIED TO STOP OIL FLOW BY BUILDING A SMALL EARTHEN DIKE BUT THE OIL HAD ALREADY REACHED DITCH AND CULVERT APPROX. 60 YARDS DOWNHILL.  HE NOTIFIED J-O'B PUMPER WHO IN TURN NOTIFIED MARTIN TRANSPORT TERMINAL MANAGER.  EMERGENCY RESPONSE COMPANY (BIG-D HAZMAT) WAS DISPATCHED TO SCENE AND SPILL WAS CONTAINED BEFORE REACHING MAJOR WATERWAY.  OIL WAS PICKED UP BY VACUUM TRUCKS.  LAND CLEANUP STARTED. MARTIN TRANSPORT, INC. HAS A POLICY THAT DRIVERS ARE NOT ALLOWED TO SIT IN THE TRUCK CABS WHILE LOADING.  THIS DRIVER WAS TERMINATED FOR FAILURE TO FOLLOW THIS RULE. THIS INCIDENT WILL BE USED AS A SAFETY TRAINING TOPIC DURING THE FIRST QUARTER OF 2001 AS A MEANS OF PREVENTING FUTURE OCCURENCES.

column168: SWA FLIGHT 826 (A/C # N647SW) WAS IN THE PROCESS OF BEING UNLOADED WHEN RAMP AGENTS DISCOVERED ELEMENTAL MERCURY ON THE CARGO BIN FLOOR.  THE CONTENTS OF THE AFT BIN WERE SECURED AND HELD FOR FURTHER INSPECTION.  AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAM WAS NOTIFIED TO COORDINATE SPILL CLEAN UP AND MAINTENANCE CONTROL WAS NOTIFIED OF THE SPILL.  THE LOCAL FAA CASFU WAS CONTACTED TO INFORM THEM OF THE INCIDENT AS WELL AS CORPORATE SAFETY. THERE WERE NO PASSENGER BAGS STOWED IN THE AFT BIN, AND THERE WAS NO VISIBLE CONTAMINATION ON ANY OF THE MAIL OR FREIGHT THAT HAD BEEN OFFLOADED FROM THE BIN.  THE EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR TESTED THE PACKAGES FOR MERCURY VAPOR USING A DIRECT READ MERCURY MONITOR AND WERE UNABLE TO POSITIVELY IDENTIFY THE SOURCE.  SUSPECT FREIGHT WAS OPENED BUT NO MERCURY SOURCE WAS IDENTIFIED. QUANTITY OF MERCURY RECOVERED WOULD BE CONSISTENT WITH THAT OF A LARGE THERMOMETER OR SMALL MERCURY SWITCH, BUT THE SOURCE OR DATE OF INITIAL INCIDENT WAS NOT DETERMINED FROM THE CLEAN UP EFFORTS.

column168: THIS IS A STANDARD FIVE COMPARTMENT GASOLINE TANKER USED TO TRANSPORT GAS TO GASOLINE STATIONS. DURING THE PROCESS OF PROPERLY SPOTTING HIS TANKER AT THE UNLOADING POINT NEAR UNDERGROUND STORAGE TANKS, THE RIGHT SIDE OF HIS TANKER STRUCK THE SHARP END OF AN OVERHEAD SIGN (SIGN SHOWING PRICE OF GASOLINE). THE SHARP END OF THE SIGN SCRAPED AND PUNCTURED A HOLE IN THE TANK ABOUT EIGHT AND A HALF FEET ABOVE THE GROUND. THE HOLE WAS TOO HIGH TO PLUG FROM THE GROUND SO THE DRIVER PROCEEDED TO UNLOAD GASOLINE FROM THE LEAKING TANK INTO THE UNDERGROUND TANK UNTIL THE LEVEL WAS BELOW THE LEAK. ABOUT 70 GALLONS LEAKED ONTO THE PARKING LOT HARD SURFACE, RAN INTO THE GUTTER, AND INTO A STORM DRAIN ABOUT FIFTY FEET SOUTH OF THE STATION. FROM THERE IT RAN 300 YARDS UNDERGROUND IN STORM DRAIN INTO A SMALL CREEK, HAPPY CREEK, A NON NAVAGATABLE WATERWAY. HAZARDOUS MATERIAL CLEANUP WAS DONE BY INDUSTRIAL MARINE SERVICE OF NORFOLK,VIRGINIA. IT IS BELIEVED THAT ALL GASOLINE WAS CONTAINED BY BOOMS PLACED ACROSS HAPPY CREEK AND IMS CLEANING UP THE PARKING LOT AREA.

column168: A TRAILER CONTAINING WASTE PHOTO SOLUTION ARRIVED AT A TEN DAY TRANSFER STATION.  WHEN THE BACK OF THE TRAILER WAS OPENED, THE LOAD HAD TIPPED OVER AND TWO GALLON MATERIAL SPILLED OUT OF THREE 30-GALLON DRUMS.  ALL OF SPILLED MATERIAL WAS CONTAINED TO THE BACK OF THE TRAILER.  THE SPILL WAS CLEANED UP WITH ABSORBENT MATERIAL AND CONTAINERIZED.  THE CONTAINERS WERE PROPERLY CLOSED AND SECURELY REPALLETIZED WITH SHRINK WRAP.  THE SPILL GENERATED APPROXIMATELY 30 POUNDS OF WASTE WHICH WAS TRANSPORTED, ALONG WITH THE ORIGINAL WASTE, TO THE SAFETY-KLEEN FACILITY AT 960 TURNPIKE STREET IN CANTON, MA FOR TREATMENT AND DISPOSAL.  THE DRIVER WAS COUNSELED ON PROPER DRUM CLOSURE PROCEDURES AND LOAD SECUREMENT TO ENSURE NO MORE FUTURE INCIDENTS.

THE SPILL OCCURRED IN SECONDARY CONTAINMENT AREA AND WAS IMMEDIATELY CLEANED UP WITH ABSORBENT MATERIAL. THE WASTE GENERATED FROM THE SPILL WAS PLACED INTO AN 85- GALLON SALVAGE DRUM ALONG WITH THE LEAKING DRUM.  THE SPILL GENERATED APPROXIMATELY 60 POUNDS OF WASTE WHICH WAS TRANSPORTED, ALONG WITH THE ORIGINAL WASTE, TO THE SAFETY-KLEEN FACILITY AT 633 EAST 138TH STREET IN DOLTON, IL FOR TREATMENT AND DISPOSAL. EAGLE CONSTRUCTION AND ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES USED ABSORBENT PADS AND SPEEDY DRY TO RECOVER THE FREE PRODUCT.  THE ABSORBENT PADS AND FLOOR DRY WERE PLACED INTO A ROLL-OFF BOX FOR DISPOSAL. THE IMPACTED TRAILER WAS DISASSEMBLED.  THE WOOD FLOORING AND PART OF THE SIDING FROM THE TRAILER WERE ALSO PLACED INTO THE ROLL-OFF BOX FOR DISPOSAL.  THE ROLL-OFF BOX WAS TRANSPORTED TO CHEM WASTE MANAGEMENT IN CARLYSS, LOUISIANA FOR DISPOSAL.  NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORT. ENCLOSED ARE COPIES OF THE WASTE MANIFESTS.
UNLOADING PRODUCT INTO CUSTOMER'S TANK, TANK GAUGE WAS NOT WORKING PROPERLY CAUSING SPILL.  DRIVER'S HAVE BEEN NOTIFIED TO CHECK TANKS AND NOT RELIE ON CUSTOMER'S TANK GAUGE.
WHILE MAKING A DELIVERY AN OUTAGE OCCURRED WHICH WAS CONTAINED, CLEANED UP AND PROPERLY DISPOSED OF.

column42: GASOLINE INCLUDES GASOLINE MIXED WITH ETHYL ALCOHOL, WITH NOT MORE THAN 10% ALCOHOL
column168: DRIVER STAMPED UNLOADING UNLEAD WHEN FITTING TIPPED OVER AND GASOLINE SPILLED FROM FILE BOX.  TEN GALLONS SPILLED AND FIVE WENT INTO STORM DRAIN. TERMINAL WORKED WITH COUNTRY AND CITY AGENCIES TO CLEAN SURROUNDING STORM DRAINS.  A CONTRACTOR TIGHTENED LOOSE COLLAR ON FITTING AND ALL DRIVER NOTIFIED TO CHECK FOR LOOSE COLLARS BEFORE UNLOADING INTO TANK FILL.

THE DRIVER HAD ARRIVED TO HIS FACILITY FROM A CUSTOMER SITE.  WHEN HE WENT INTO THE BACK OF TRUCK, HE NOTICED SOME MOISTURE ON THE BED OF THE TRUCK. HE INSPECTED THE DRUMS HE WAS CARRYING AND DISCOVERED A 55-GALLON DRUM OF DICHLOROMETHANE HAD A PINHOLE LEAK ON THE BOTTOM OF THE DRUM. APPROXIMATELY TWO OUNCES HAD SPILLED OUT OF THE DRUM BUT NONE WAS RELEASED OUTSIDE OF THE TRUCK.  THE SPILL WAS IMMEDIATELY CLEANED UP THE ABSORBENT MATERIAL AND THE CONTAINERIZED ALONG WITH THE LEAKING DRUM INTO AN 85-GALLON SALVAGE DRUM.  THE SPILL GENERATED APPROXIMATELY ONE POUND OF WASTE WHICH WAS TRANSPORTED, ALONG WITH THE ORIGINAL WASTE, TO THE SAFETY-KLEEN FACILITY AT 300 CANAL STREET IN LAWRENCE, MA FOR TREATMENT AND DISPOSAL.  THE DRIVER WAS COUNSELED ON PROPER DRUM INSPECTION PROCEDURES TO ENSURE NO MORE FUTURE INCIDENTS.

A 55-GALLON STEEL DRUM WAS AT A TEN DAY TRANSFER FACILITY'S STAGING AREA. THE OUTSIDE TEMPERATURE BEGAN TO INCREASE AND THE FLAMMABLE SOLID WITHIN THE DRUM EXPANDED.  THE LID TO THE DRUM DID NOT HAVE A GASKET AND APPROXIMATELY ONE AND HALF PINTS SPILLED INTO SECONDARY CONTAINMENT AREA. WHEN THE SPILL WAS DISCOVERED, IT WAS IMMEDIATELY CLEANED UP WITH ABSORBENT MATERIAL AND CONTAINERIZED.  A NEW LID WAS PLACED ONTO THE 55-GALLON DRUM FOR FUTURE SHIPMENT.  THE SPILL PRODUCED APPROXIMATELY 2 POUNDS OF WASTE WHICH WAS TRANSPORTED, ALONG WITH THE ORIGINAL WASTE, TO THE SAFETY-KLEEN FACILITY AT 1722 COOPER CREEK ROAD IN DENTON, TX FOR TREATMENT AND DISPOSAL.  THE DRIVER WAS COUNSELED ON PROPER DRUM INSPECTION AND CLOSURE PROCEDURES TO ENSURE NO MORE FUTURE INCIDENTS.

A DRUM WAS IN STORAGE AT A TEN DAY TRANSFER FACILITY AND WHILE IT WAS BEING MOVED, THE DRUM WAS HIT BY A FORKLIFT.  APPROXIMATELY ONE QUART OF FLAMMABLE SOLVENT SPILLED ONTO THE FLOOR IN A SECONDARY CONTAINMENT AREA. THE SPILL WAS IMMEDIATELY CLEANED UP WITH ABSORBENT MATERIAL AND CONTAINERIZED ALONG WITH THE DAMAGED 55-GALLON DRUM IN AN 85-GALLON SALVAGE DRUM. THE SPILL GENERATED APPROXIMATELY FIVE POUNDS OF WASTE WHICH WAS TRANSPORTED, ALONG WITH THE ORIGINAL WASTE, TO THE SAFETY-KLEEN FACILITY AT 1200 SYLVAN STREET IN LINDEN, NJ FOR TREATMENT AND DISPOSAL. THE FORKLIFT DRIVER WAS COUNSELED ON PROPER FORKLIFT HANDLING TO ENSURE NO MORE FUTURE INCIDENTS.

THE DRIVER WAS UNLOADING HIS TRUCK AT THE FACILITY.  WHILE UNLOADING THE WASTE, HE WAS RECHECKING THE BUNGS ON THE DRUMS AND CRACKED ONE OF THEM WHEN HE WAS TIGHTENING IT.  APPROXIMATELY ONE AND HALF GALLONS OF THE METHANOL AND XYLENE MIXTURE SPILLED INTO THE BACK OF THE TRUCK. THE SPILL WAS IMMEDIATELY CLEANED UP ABSORBENT MATERIALS SO THAT ALL THE WASTE WAS CONTAINED IN THE TRUCK.  THE DAMAGED DRUM AND THE WASTE GENERATED FROM THE SPILL WERE PLACED INTO A 30-GALLON OVERPACK DRUM. THE SPILL GENERATED APPROXIMATELY 15 POUNDS OF WASTE WHICH WAS TRANSPORTED, ALONG WITH THE ORIGINAL WASTE, TO THE SAFETY-KLEEN FACILITY AT 1200 SYLVAN STREET IN LINDEN, NJ FOR TREATMENT AND DISPOSAL. THE DRIVER WAS COUNSELED ON PROPER DRUM CLOSURE PROCEDURES TO ENSURE NO MORE FUTURE INCIDENTS.

column168: INVESTIGATION AT THE SCENE REVEALED"  VEHICLE #1 (FUEL TANKER) WAS TRAVELING ON THE RAMP FROM SH 73 SOUTH TO I - 295 NORTH IN MT. LAUREL TWP. VEHICLE #1 WAS TRAVELING AT TOO FAST A SPEED AND BEGAN TO LOSE CONTROL OF THE VEHICLE.  VEHICLE #1 STRUCK THE OUTSIDE CURB AND OVERTURNED.  VEHICLE #1 LANDED ON THE GRASSY AREA BETWEEN THE RAMP AND THE MAIN LINE WITH THE TOP OF THE TRAILER ON ITS SIDE FACING THE RAMP.  THE CENTER LOADING PORT HAD BEEN DAMAGED IN THE ROLL OVER CAUSING 1200 TO 1400 GALLONS OF FUEL TO BE SPILLED.

I WAS SUPPOSED TO DELIVER A LOAD OF DIESEL FUEL TO AMERICAN CONCRETE. ACCORDING TO INFORMATION I HAD, THE LOAD TO GO TO AMERICAN CONCRETE IN JOHNSON.  I GOT THERE AFTER HOURS, THERE WERE  2 TRAILERS BLOCKING THE VIEW OF THE TANK, I HAD TO STRETCH OUT 40 FOOT OF HOSE TO REACH IT.  I DID NOT HAVE A CLEAR VIEW OF THE TANK, THERE WAS NO LIGHTING, THE GAUGE ON THE TANK DIDN'T WORK.  I CRAWLED ON TOP OF THE TANK WITH MY GAUGING STICK AND COULDN'T FIND ANY ACCESS INTO THE TANK TO MEASURE THE FUEL IN IT.  I ASSUMED THE TANK WOULD HOLD IT.  I RUN APPROXIMATELY 3746 GALLONS INTO THE TANK AND RUM IT OVER.  THIS WOULD NOT HAVE HAPPENED IF I WOULD HAVE HAD A CLEAR VIEW OF THE TANK, BEEN ABLE TO GAUGE THE TANK AND IF THE GAUGE HAD BEEN WORKING, AND IF I WOULD HAVE HAD THE PROPER INFORMATION ON WHERE IT WAS TO GO.  THIS ALL TOOK PLACE AFTER HOURS WITH NO ONE THERE TO TELL ME ANY DIFFERENT.  WHEN I WAS DIRECTED TO TAKE THE REST OF THE LOAD TO WEST DES MOINES, AFTER NUMEROUS PHONE CALLS AND DETECTIVE  WORK (THE DES MOINES PHONE BOOK HAS ALL ADDRESSES FOR AMERICAN CONCRETE IN DES MOINES), AND GOT THERE I COULD NOT FIND A GAUGE ON THAT TANK.  NEITHER TANK WAS MARKED TO IDENTIFY WHAT WAS TO GO IN THEM.

THE DRIVER AND THE OWNER OF THE SERVICE STATION THEN PUT DOWN THE CARDBOARD ON THE GROUND, SPRINKLED THE CARDBOARD WITH THE KITTY LITTER TO TRY TO ABSORB ANY LIQUID AND SET THE BUCKETS UNDER THE LIDS TO CATCH ANY LIQUID DRIPPING. column168: THE RELEASE OCCURRED WHILE THE TANKER TRUCK WAS EN ROUTE TO ITS DESTINATION ON HIGHWAY 20, WHICH IS AN UNDIVIDED TWO LANE ROAD WITH ONE LANE IN EACH DIRECTION.  THE LAND SURROUNDING THE RELEASE IS A RURAL UNDEVELOPED AREA. THE RELEASE WAS CAUSED BY THE TANKER TRUCK TRAVELING WEST BOUND INTO A 35 MPH CURVE WITH A 12 DEGREE PITCH SUPER AT APPROXIMATELY 40 TO 50 MPH WHERE CONTROL OF HIS VEHICLE WAS LOST CAUSING THE TRACTOR AND TWO TRAILERS TO OVERTURNED THE LEAD TRAILER CAME TO REST ON ITS TOPS, THE SECOND ON ITS SIDE.  THE DRIVER OF THE TRACTOR WAS KILLED AT THE SCENE FROM IMPACT AND A FUEL FIRE FROM THE TRUCKS FUEL TANKS.  THE LEAD TRAILERS DOME LID WAS RIPPED OPEN DUMPING 5538 GALLONS OF FUEL OIL INTO THE BAR DITCH & RUNNING OVER THE ROAD WAY INTO THE YAQUINA RIVER.  THE SECOND TRAILER ALSO CAME TO REST ON ITS SIDE, APPROXIMATELY 90 TO 100 GALLONS WAS LOST THROUGH THE VENTING SYSTEM THAT IS DESIGNED FOR VAPOR RELEASE IN TRANSIT.  THE LOSS OF PRODUCT HAD NO CONTRIBUTION TO THE DRIVERS DEATH. APPROXIMATELY 4630 GALLONS ENTER THE YAQUINA RIVER.  PRIVATE HAZ MAT COMPANIES IN OREGON & WASHINGTON ALONG WITH COAST GUARD, EPA, DEQ, FISH & GAME AND VARIOUS OTHER AGENCIES ASSISTED IN CLEAN UP AND MONITORING.  THE OIL THAT WAS RETRIEVED FROM THE RIVER WAS TRANSPORTED TO OIL RE-REFINING, 4150 N SUTTLE RD, PORTLAND, OR.  97217.  WITH ENCLOSED DOCUMENTS.  THE WASTE WAS TRANSPORTED TO WASTE MANAGEMENT 13649 SW HIGHWAY 18, MCMINVILLE, OR, 97128.  AS A NON HAZARDOUS WASTE, WITH ENCLOSED DOCUMENTS.

FILE: 3038 D. SHIPPER: ROCHE DIAGNOSTIC, AWB#DIN 20027838374PVD. ON 01/06/2001 AT 0035 A SPILL WAS REPORTED IN THE TRAILER OF A TRUCK AT BUILDING E OF OUR SORT FACILITY LOCATED AT ABX AIR, INC., 145 HUNTER DRIVE, WILIMINGTON, OHIO 45177.  PART TIME HAZ MAT TECHNICIANS TIMOTHY HINES, ROBERT HARPER, EDWOOD BOHL, AND DONALD OSBORNE, ALONG WITH HAZARDOUS MATERIALS COORDINATOR BRUCE CUNNIGHAM, AND CERT SUPERVISOR KAREN SCHATZAMANN, DONNED PROPER PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT AND RESPONDED.  UPON ARRIVAL THEY FOUND A BROWN FIBERBOARD BOX WITH VIABLE SIGNS OF LEAKAGE ON THE OUTER PACKAGE. THIS PACKAGE WAS MARKED AND LABELED, "SODIUM HYDROXIDE SOLUTION UN 1824", CLASS 8/CAO.  THE TEAM ENTERED THE TRUCK TRAILER AND BEGAN THEIR INSPECTION AND CLEAN UP.  UPON ENTERING THE TRAILER, THE TEAM FOUND A SKID OF FREIGHT, SHRINK WRAPPED, THAT HAD A "LOAD SHIFT" DURING TRANSIT, CAUSING THE FREIGHT TO FALL OVER.  ONE PACKAGE WAS VISIBLY LEAKING.  AFTER IDENTIFICATION OF THE PRODUCT, THE TEAM FOCUSED ON INSPECTING THIS PACKAGE.  UPON INSPECTION OF THIS PACKAGE THEY FOUND IT TO CONTAIN 6 X 1.3 L, PLASTIC RECEPTACLES WITH FRICTION TYPE CLOSURES, AND NO ABSORBANT MATERIALS  ONE OF THESE PLASTIC RECEPTACLES HAD BEEN PUNCTURED NEAR THE BOTTOM, CAUSING IT TO LEAK IT'S ENTIRE CONTENTS.  THIS WAS VISIBLE DUE TO THE DAMAGE TO THE OUTER PACKAGE.  THE TEAM PLACED THE ITEMS BACK INTO THE BOX, RESEALED IT AND PLACED IT INTO 2 PLASTIC BAGS WITH ABSORBENT MATERIAL.  ONCE THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED THE TEAM BEGAN TO NEUTRALIZE ALL AREAS IN CONTACT WITH THE PRODUCT.  THEY PLACED THE BAGGED SHIPMENT INTO A RECOVERY DRUM AND FORWARDED IT ONTO IT'S DESTINATION. THE AREA WAS NEUTRALIZED BEFORE NORMAL WORK OPERATIONS WERE RESUMED. THERE WERE NO EMPLOYEES INVOLVED. THIS WAS PROPERTY MARKED,  LABELED AND HAD THE APPROPRIATE HAZ CERTIFICATION ACCOMPANYING THIS SHIPMENT. A COPY OF THE SHIPPER'S DECLARATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS WILL ACCOMPANY THIS REPORT. THERE ARE PICTURES ON FILE IN THE HAZ MAT OFFICE AT ILN. CLEAR OF SCENE 0228.

THE EMPLOYEE WAS ADVISED WHAT IT WAS AND RETURNED TO THE WORK AREA. NO MEDICAL ATTENTION WAS NEEDED, NO CHANGES WITH THIS EMPLOYEE. NO FOLLOW UP NEEDED. BULKMATIC EMPLOYEE JAMES G. JOHNSON WAS IN THE PROCESS OF TRANSLOADING SULFURIC ACID INTO A BULK LIQUID TRAILER BY MEANS OF COMPRESSED AIR WHEN A PVC VALVE COUPLER BROKE.  MR. JOHNSON WAS NOT WEARING HIS PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT AT THE TIME, AND WAS SPLASHED WITH ACID OVER APPROXIMATELY 80% OF HIS BODY.  MR. JOHNSON IS STILL HOSPITALIZED AT THE TIME OF THIS REPORT. A SECOND EMPLOYEE, TAURUS MOORE, RECEIVED MINOR ACID BURNS WHILE ASSISTING MR. JOHNSON.  HE WAS TREATED AND RELEASED FROM THE HOSPITAL THE DAY OF THE INCIDENT. EMS, FIRE DEPARTMENT AND HAZMAT PERSONNEL WERE CALLED TO THE SCENE IMMEDIATELY.  THE RAILCAR WAS CAPPED TO PREVENT FURTHER SPILLAGE.  TOTAL AMOUNT ESTIMATED AT APPROXIMATELY 1,800 GALLONS. RUN OFF WENT INTO CONTAINMENT POND WHICH HAS BEEN TREATED AND RETURNED TO NORMAL CONDITION.

INCIDENT OCCURRED WHILE AN H. JOHN DAVIS TRUCK WAS BEING FILLED UNDER THE LOADING RACK OF LLOYD J. NOLAN, INC. UPON RELEASE OF THE LOADING ARM FROM THE FILLING POSITION, THE VALVE ON THE LOADING ARM RE-OPENED, AND RELEASED APPROXIMATELY 40 GALLONS OF HEATING OIL.  THE PRODUCT SPILLED OVER TOP OF THE TRUCK AND ONTO THE PARKING AREA UNDERNEATH. DAVIS PERSONNEL USED ON-SITE OIL ABSORBENT MATERIAL TO STOP THE FLOW OF PRODUCT FROM GETTING INTO ANY STORM DRAINS, OR WELLS.  IN ADDITION, BOTH SCHLIER'S TOWING AND TEEM ENVIRONMENTAL, WERE CALLED TO BOTH PROVIDE ADDITIONAL ABSORBENT MATERIAL, AND CLEANUP PROTOCOL. TEEM ENVIRONMENTAL WAS RESPONSIBLE FOR THE FINAL "MOP-UP" OF THE INCIDENT, AND FOR REMOVAL OF THE OIL-LADEN ABSORBENT MATERIAL.  THE MATERIAL WAS COLLECTED INTO DRUMS, AND REMOVED TO WASTE RECOVERY SYSTEMS, IN MYERSTOWN, PA. NO OIL GOT INTO ANY STORM SEWER, DRAIN, OR ANY OTHER COLLECTION POINT.  ALL PRODUCT WAS CONTAINED WITHIN THE FACILITY. TO PREVENT FUTURE OCCURRENCES OF THIS TYPE, TWO STEPS WERE TAKEN. FIRST, THE VALVE OPERATION WAS CORRECTED AND REPAIRED.  SECONDLY, ADDITIONAL PROCEDURES WERE INSTITUTED WITH DRIVER PERSONNEL TO ENHANCE BOTH THE SAFE FILLING OF DELIVERY VEHICLES, AND THE PROPER SHUT-DOWN TECHNIQUES OF THIS PARTICULAR LOADING VALVE.

CSX TRANSPORTATION'S HAZMAT DEPT. RECEIVED A CALL FROM RUDOLPH BARNETT WITH CSXT'S FREIGHT DAMAGE DEPT. REGARDING A BOX CAR, MSRC 5012, LOADED WITH 50 LB PLASTIC BAGS OF POTASSIUM NITRATE.  THE CAR HAD BEEN DELIVERED TO THE CONSIGNEE IN TAMPA, FL.  WHEN THE CONSIGNEE OPENED THE CAR, THEY FOUND THAT THE LOAD HAD SHIFTED AND SEVERAL BAGS FELL ONTO THE FLOOR AND BUSTED OPEN SPILLING PRODUCT INSIDE THE BOX CAR.  HAZMAT CONTACTED A MR WAYNE WILSON, AT THE CONSIGNEE'S FACILITY TO DETERMINE IF THEY REQUIRED ANY ASSISTANCE. MR. WILSON REPORTED THE PLASTIC BAGS WERE STACKED ON PALLETS AND SHRINK WRAPPED.  IT APPEARS THE LOAD SHIFTED AND 10 TO 15 BAGS SLIPPED  OFF THE PALLETS AND FELL ONTO THE FLOOR OF THE CAR.  SOME OF THE BAGS SPLIT IN THE CORNERS SPILLING SOME PRODUCT.  HE ESTIMATED NO MORE THAN 20 LBS OF PRODUCT HAD ACTUALLY SPILLED.  NO PRODUCT WAS RELEASED OUTSIDE THE CAR.  HE INDICATED THIS KIND OF THING HAPPENS ON OCCASION.  HIS PEOPLE WILL UNLOAD THE CAR.  THE SPILLED PRODUCT WILL BE SHOVELED UP AND PLACED IN THEIR BULK POTASSIUM NITRATE BIN.

column168: ON SATURDAY, 1-27-01, AT APPROXIMATELY 1540 HOURS, PERSONNEL AT THE UNION PACIFIC RAILROAD YARD AT LIVONIA, LOUISIANA OBSERVED A SMALL STREAM OF LIQUID RUNNING DOWN THE SIDE OF TANK CAR GATX 19147. THE CAR WAS SPOTTED OVER THE DRIP PANS ON THE HAZ/MAT TRACK AND HAD BEEN THERE FOR SEVERAL DAYS. IT SHOULD BE NOTED THAT THE CAR HAD ARRIVED AT LIVONIA 0N 1/7/01 AND WAS FOUND TO BE OVERLOADED BY WEIGHT. UPON NOTIFICATION UPRR MANAGER ENVIRONMENTAL FIELD OPERATIONS, T.M. ROBINSON RESPONDED TO THE SCENE. ROBINSON'S INSPECTION REVEALED THAT THE CAR WAS SHELL FULL AND THE EXPANDING LIQUID HAD BURST THE FRANGIBLE DISC IN THE SAFETY VENT. SATURDAY WAS THE WARMEST DAY IN THE AREA FOR THE LAST SEVERAL WEEKS. NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE TO THE LOUISIANA STATE POLICE, LOUISIANA DEPT. OF ENV. QUALITY, POINTE COUPEE PARISH, HONEYWELL INTL, THE SHIPPER AND EAGLE CONSTR & ENV. INC. EAGLE RESPONDED WITH PERSONNEL AND EQUIPMENT, INCLUDING A CARGO TANK TRUCK. THE LOAD WAS REDUCED AN ESTIMATED 2500 GALLONS, THE DISC WAS REPLACED AND THE CAR SECURED. THE SEVERAL GALLONS OF SPILLAGE ON THE CAR AND THE DRIP PANS WAS REMEDIATED USING A MILD SOLUTION OF BAKING SODA AND WATER.

UPON ARRIVAL, REEDER REQUESTED TO OPEN THE CAR TO DETERMINE IF IT WAS OVERLOADED. SHILLING ADVISED AGAINST THAT CITING THE PRODUCT WAS AN EXTREMELY LOW ODOR THRESHOLD. column168: ON 01/02/2001 DENNIS JOHNSON, MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY RESPONDED TO A 19 CAR DERAILMENT OF THE NOGALES SUBDIVISION. HIS INVESTIGATION DETERMINED THAT THREE TANK CARS RELEASED PRODUCT. THE ABOVE TANK CAR SUSTAINED A PUNCTURE TO THE END OF THE CAR WHICH CAUSED THE RELEASE. ALL REMAINING PRODUCT IN THE TANK CAR WAS TRANSLOADED INTO TANK TRUCKS AND REMOVED FROM THE SCENE.

LANE A. SEKAVEC, MANAGER-CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY WAS NOTIFIED OF THE DERAILMENT OF AN INTERMODAL TRAIN WITH AT LEAST TWO CONTAINERS OF HAZ-MAT DERAILED. ON ARRIVAL, MR.SEKAVEC FOUND CONTAINERS CRXCU241411 AND CRXU102358 TO BE APPROXIMATELY 20 BELOW GRADE, DERAILED INTO A STORM SEWER OUTFALL THAT RUNS INTO THE KANSAS RIVER. THESE TWO CONTAINERS WERE IN THE SAME WELL OF THE CAR, UNDER AN EMPTY CONTAINER. THE WATERWAYS WAS PREDOMINANTLY DRY WITH JUST A MINIMAL AMOUNT OF WATER RUNNING THROUGH IT. INSPECTION OF THE SHIPPING PAPERS SHOWED THE MATERIALS TO BE CHLORONITROBENZENES AND TRICHLOISOCYANURIC ACID. INSPECTION OF THE CONTAINERS SHOWED NO LEAKS. WRECKING CONTRACTORS CONSTRUCTED A BERM DOWNSTREAM TO CONTAIN ANY LEAKAGE SHOULD THE CONTAINERS RUPTURE. DURING WRECKING OPERATIONS, THE CONTAINERS WERE REGULARLY EVALUATED TO DETERMINE STABILITY OF THE LOADS AND DOORS. AFTER THE EMPTY CONTAINER WAS REMOVED, THE WRECKING CONTRACTOR BEGAN REMOVAL OF THE TWO CRXU CONTAINERS. THE LOAD ON CRXU102358 HAD SHIFTED AND FALLEN AGAINST THE DOORS, REQUIRING THEM TO BE CHAINED TO PREVENT THE BARRELS OF PRODUCT FROM ESCAPING. THIS COMPLETED, THE CONTAINER WAS REMOVED FROM THE CREEK BED AND PLACED ON A CHASSIS FOR REMOVAL TO ARMOURDALE INTERMODAL FACILITY. WRECKING CREWS BEGAN REMOVING CRXU241411 FROM THE CREEK. AS THE CONTAINER WAS BEING MOVED, PRODUCT WAS OBSERVED COMING FROM THE CONTAINER. HAZ-MAT RESPONSE PERSONNEL PLACED A TEMPORARY PATCH ON THE CONTAINER WHICH ALLOWED IT TO BE REMOVED FROM THE CREEK. AFTER UPRIGHTING THE CONTAINER, MR SEKAVEC AND HAZ-MAT RESPONSE PERSONNEL EVALUATED THE CONTAINER AND PLACED FOUR TEMPORARY PATCHES ON THE CONTAINER TO SECURE IT FOR MOVEMENT TO THE ARMOUDALE INTERMODAL FACILITY. BOTH CONTAINERS WERE SECURED FOR THE EVENING. AN INSPECTION THE FOLLOWING MORNING REVEALED NO FURTHER LEAKS OF PRODUCT. OVER THE FOLLOWING WEEK, THE CONTAINERS WERE BOTH TRANSLOADED INTO ROAD TRAILERS IN PREPARATION FOR TRANSPORTATION BACK TO THE MANUFACTURER.

KENNETH SIMPSON, MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY WAS ADVISED OF A LEAKING TANK CAR IN THE LONGVIEW YARD. SIMPSON CONTRACTED MICROTECH ENVIRONMENTAL TO RESPOND. column168: DEAN C. COOPER, MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS CONTACTED BY TIM POST, MANAGER, ICTF, REPORTING A LEAKING CONTAINER.  MANAGER POST STATED THE ABOVE CONTAINER WAS NOTED LEAKING WHILE PARKED IN GREEN ROW, SPACE 008. DEVELOPED ICTF SECURITY NOTED LIQUID DRIPPING FROM THE NOSE AREA OF THE CONTAINER AND NOTIFIED MANAGER POST, WHO MADE ARRANGEMENTS TO MOVE THE CONTAINER TO THE CUSTOM'S DOCK FOR INSPECTION.  UPON OPENING THE REAR DOORS OF THE CONTAINER AND FOUND NO PLACARDS, AND THE RAIL WAYBILL SHOWED THE CONTENTS TO BE FAK (FREIGHT ALL KINDS).  UPON OPENING THE DOORS, DEVELOPED THE LADING CONSISTED OF 35 DRUMS,  FLOOR LOADED, AND SECURED WITH WHAT APPEARED TO BE GOOD BLOCKING AND BRACING PER AAR PAMPHLET 6C.  THE DRUMS WERE MARKED WITH FLAMMABLE AND SUBSIDIARY POISON LABELS.  AT THE TIME, THERE WAS NO WAY TO DETERMINE WHICH DRUM WAS LEAKING.  CONTACTED NYK LINE WHO PROVIDED THEIR SHIPPER.  BDP INTERNATIONAL, AND ALSO PROVIDED A COPY OF THE HAZARD DECLARATION, WHICH SHOWED THE CONTENTS TO BE ISOBUTYRONITRILE.  CONTACT WITH THE ACTUAL SHIPPER, EASTMAN, CONFIRMED THE CONTENTS, AND A MSDS WAS FAXED FOR REVIEW.  ARRANGEMENTS WERE MADE TO REMOVE THE DRUMS TO INSPECT FOR THE SOURCE OF THE LEAK(S).  WHILE OFF LOADING THE DRUMS, OBSERVED ALL THE DRUMS HAD VARYING DEGREES OF DAMAGE FROM SPINNING WHILE IN TRANSIT.  THIS IS COMMON WHEN THE DRUMS ARE NOT STAGED TIGHTLY AGAINST EACH OTHER WHEN LOADED.  IT WAS ALSO NOTED THAT THE DRUMS WERE THE NEWER STYLE WITH THE RECESSED SIDE WALL ROLLING HOOPS. WHILE THE NEWER STYLE DRUMS ALLOW FOR A ROW OF 4 DRUMS ACROSS THE CONTAINER, THEY ALLOW A 1/4 INCH GAP AT THE END OF EACH ROW.  IF THE INDIVIDUAL ROWS OF DRUMS ARE NOT OFF SET IN THE LOADING PROCESS, THEY WILL SHIFT AND ALLOW FOR MOVEMENT DURING TRANSPORTATION.  IT IS HIGHLY RECOMMENDED THAT WHEN THESE TYPES OF DRUMS ARE UTILIZED, THEY BE LOADED IN A STAGGERED 4-3-4 PATTERN THAT WILL ALLOW THE DRUMS TO NEST AND STAY TIGHT DURING TRANSPORTATION.  4 ROWS INTO THE CONTAINER FROM THE REAR DOORS, LOCATED 1 DRUM, SECOND OUT FROM THE RIGHT SIDE WALL, THAT HAD THE BOTTOM CHIME WORN THROUGH.  THE CHIME HAD A FLAT SIDE SURFACE FROM ABRADING AN ADJACENT DRUM, ROUGHLY 3 INCHES LONG, WHICH PRODUCED A 3 INCH CRACK. ESTIMATED LOSS WAS 17 GALLONS.  THE DRUM WAS PATCHED AND PLACED INTO AN OVER PACK FOR SECUREMENT.  THE DRUM DIRECTLY IN FRONT OF THIS ONE, WAS ALSO LEAKING AT THE BOTTOM CHIME, WITH SIMILAR TYPE DAMAGE.  ESTIMATED LOSS WAS 30 GALLONS.  THE DRUM WAS PATCHED AND PLACED INTO AN OVER PACK FOR SECUREMENT.  ANOTHER DRUM IN THE 5TH ROW, SECOND OUT FROM THE LEFT SIDE WALL, WAS FOUND TO BE COMPLETELY EMPTY.  THE DRUM HAD SPUN IN PLACE AND WORN THROUGH THE BOTTOM OF THE CHIME, CREATING A CRACK ROUGHLY 9 INCHES LONG.  AN ADDITIONAL DRUM WAS NOTED LEAKING FROM THE BOTTOM IN THE 2ND ROW FROM THE NOSE.  WHILE IN THE PROCESS OF INVERTING THE DRUM TO REMOVE IT, THE BOTTOM HEAD BLEW OUT, RELEASING APPROXIMATELY 30 GALLONS OF PRODUCT BEFORE THE DRUM COULD BE RIGHTED.  THE LOOSE

column62: Defective Component or Device; Water Damage
column168: DEAN C. COOPER, MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS CONTACTED BY RMCC REPORTING A LEAKING IM TANK AT THE ICTF.  MANAGER COOPER DROVE TO THE ICTF AND LOCATED THE ABOVE IM TANK IN EAST 5, SPACE 338.  A SMALL POOL OF LIQUID (LESS THAN ONE PINT) WAS ON THE PAVEMENT DIRECTLY BELOW THE LEFT DRIP TUBE THAT ATTACHES TO THE TOP SPILL BOX.  A STRONG PUNGENT ODOR WAS NOTED, INDICATING THE LISTED PRODUCT HAD BEEN RELEASED.  THE LIQUID ON THE GROUND WAS NEUTRALIZED AND COVERED WITH ABSORBENT.  INSPECTION OF THE TOP VALVE COMPARTMENT NOTED LIQUID DRIPPING FROM THE LIQUID LINE FLANGE, DIRECTLY ABOVE THE BALL VALVE.  THE 4 BOLTS ON THE FLANGE WERE TIGHT, INDICATING A PROBLEM WITH THE GASKET MATERIAL, AND AN OBVIOUS PRODUCT BY PASS OF THE BALL VALVE.  SEVERAL OUNCES OF PRODUCT WAS IN THE CATCH BASIN SURROUNDING THE VALVES, WHICH WAS NEUTRALIZED AND COVERED WITH ABSORBENT. THE AIR VALVE WAS CRACKED OPEN TO RELIEVE THE INTERNAL PRESSURE WITHIN THE TANK.  ONCE THE PRODUCT STOPPED LEAKING FROM THE LIQUID LINE VALVE, THE AIR LINE VALVE WAS SECURED.  THE IM TANK WAS THEN MOVED TO THE CUSTOM'S DOCK, WHERE IT COULD BE ISOLATED AND PROPERLY CONTAINED PENDING REPAIRS. CONTACTED MATSON CUSTOMER SERVICE CENTER, PHOENIX, AZ., AND WAS ADVISED THEY HAD NO RECORD OF THIS MOVE.  CONTACTED MATSON IN OAKBROOK TERRACE, IL., AND THEY WERE UNABLE TO PROVIDE ANY RECORD OF THIS SHIPMENT EVEN THOUGH THEY SHOWED AS THE SHIPPER OF RECORD ON THE RAIL BILLING.  FINALLY CONTACTED BAYER CORP., PITTSBURGH, AND DEVELOPED THIS WAS THEIR PRODUCT,AND IT HAD BEEN SHIPPED FROM THE BAYER FACILITY LOCATED AT BAYTOWN, TEXAS. BAYER MADE ARRANGEMENTS TO HAVE TRANSLOADING ENVIRONMENTAL, REMOVE THE FAULTY VALVE, REBUILD IT, AND REINSTALL THE VALVE.  PRECAUTIONS WERE TAKEN TO PREVENT MOISTURE AND AIR INSIDE THE TANK WHILE THE VALVE WAS BEING REBUILT.  ONCE THE VALVE WAS REINSTALLED ONTO THE TANK, A NITROGEN BLANKET WAS PLACED INTO THE TANK TO PROPERLY PROTECT THE COMMODITY.  ONCE THE REPAIRS WERE MADE, THE TANK WAS MOVED SEVERAL TIMES TO ENSURE PROPER SECUREMENT.  THE TANK WAS THEN RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT ONTO THE CONSIGNEE.

column168: DEAN C COOPER, MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS CONTACTED BY RMCC REPORTING A LEAKING TANK CAR IN PHOENIX, AZ.  MANAGER COOPER CONTACTED MYO DEMPSEY, WHO STATED THE CAR DEPARTMENT HAD BEEN INSPECTING A INBOUND TRAIN IN YARD TRACK #3, AND NOTED LIQUID DRIPPING FROM THE ABOVE TANK CAR. MANAGER COOPER CONTACTED ERI AND HAD THEM RESPOND TO REPAIR THE LEAK.  UPON THE ARRIVAL OF ERI, DEVELOPED THE LEAK CONSISTED OF 1 DROP EVERY 5 SECONDS, AND THE MATERIAL WAS EVAPORATING.  INSPECTION OF THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE DEVELOPED THE SOURCE OF THE LEAK TO BE FROM THE FLANGE WHERE THE BOTTOM OUTLET ATTACHES TO THE BELLY OF THE TANK CAR.  EFFORTS TO TIGHTEN THE 8 HEX HEAD BOLTS SLOWED THE LEAK, BUT FAILED TO COMPLETELY STOP THE LEAK. AFTER SOME EFFORT IN CONTACTING THE SHIPPER, MANAGER COOPER WAS ADVISED THE CONSIGNEE, TOSCO, WAS ENROUTE TO REPAIR THE CAR.  AFTER TALKING TO THE TOSCO REPRESENTATIVE LATER IN THE DAY, DEVELOPED THERE WAS A BREAK DOWN IN COMMUNICATIONS, AS THEY UNDERSTOOD FROM THE SHIPPER, THAT THE CAR HAD BEEN REPAIRED.  FURTHER DEVELOPED THAT TOSCO HAD NO WAY TO REPAIR THE CURRENT CONDITION OF THE CAR.  AT THIS POINT.  ARRANGEMENTS WERE MADE TO OFF LOAD THE TANK CAR AND TRANSPORT THE PRODUCT BY TRUCK THE TOSCO TERMINAL.  AS THE TRUCKS WOULD NOT BE AVAILABLE UNTIL THE NEXT MORNING , ERI HAD A REPRESENTATIVE PROTECT THE CAR THROUGH THE NIGHT.  ONCE THE CAR WAS MADE EMPTY, THE PRODUCT WAS DELIVERED TO THE TOSCO TERMINAL.  MUREX WILL ARRANGE TO SHOP THE CAR FOR INSPECTION UPON IT'S RETURN TO TEXAS.

column168: SEE ATTACHED EXTRACT FROM CA HIGHWAY PATROL TRAFFIC COLLISION REPORT #2001010111. ACTION TAKEN TO PREVENT FUTURE INCIDENTS INCLUDE DISCUSSION OF INCIDENT WITH OTHER DRIVERS, AWARENESS OF ROADSIDE WARNINGS, AND DEFENSIVE DRIVING TECHNIQUES. FACTS NOTIFICATION:  MY PARTNER (K. JONG #10825) AND I RECEIVED A RADIO CALL OF A TRAFFIC COLLISION WITH AN AMBULANCE ROLLING, AT 0146 HOURS.  WE RESPONDED FROM PONY EXPRESS TRAIL EAST OF SLY PARK ROAD AND ARRIVED AT THE TRAFFIC COLLISION SCENE, STATE ROUTE 49 (SOUTHBOUND) NORTH OF UNION MINE ROAD (SOUTH), AT 0210 HOURS.  ALL TIMES, SPEEDS, AND DISTANCES ARE APPROXIMATE. MEASUREMENTS WERE TAKEN BY ROLATAPE AND PATROL VEHICLE ODOMETER. SCENE DESCRIPTION: STATE ROUTE 49 NORTH OF UNION MINE ROAD (SOUTH) IS A TWO-WAY, NORTH-SOUTH, ASPHALT SURFACE ROADWAY THAT IS LOCATED IN UNINCORPORATED EL DORADO COUNTY. THE NORTHBOUND AND SOUTHBOUND TRAFFIC LANES ARE SEPARATED BY PAINTED DOUBLE PARALLEL SOLID YELLOW LINES AND RAISED AMBER REFLECTORS.  THE TRAFFIC LANES ARE BORDERED BY ASPHALT SHOULDERS.  THE POSTED RECOMMENDED SPEED LIMIT IN THE AREA OF THE TRAFFIC COLLISION IS 15 MILES PER HOUR.  THERE ARE TWO POSTED ADVISORY SIGNS, ONE MILE APART, WARNING: "HILL TRUCKS USE LOW GEAR NEXT 3 MI", "HILL TRUCKS USE LOW GEAR NEXT 2 MI".  REFER TO FACTUAL DIAGRAM. PARTIES: PARTY #1 (LLOYD ARCHIE GLEAVES) WAS LOCATED LYING ON AMBULANCE GURNEY IN THE REAR OF THE EL DORADO COUNTY MEDIC UNIT, UPON OUR ARRIVAL.  PARTY #1 WAS IDENTIFIED AS THE DRIVER OF VEHICLE #1 BY HIS VALID CALIFORNIA DRIVER'S LICENSE, HIS OWN ADMISSIONS, HIS INJURIES, AND STATEMENTS.  VEHICLE #1 (FRHT TRUCK TRACTOR/MSPP TANK TRAILER) WAS LOCATED LYING UPSIDE-DOWN ON THE ASPHALT/DIRT SHOULDER, WEST OF STATE ROUTE 49 NORTH OF UNION MINE ROAD (SOUTH), UPON OUR ARRIVAL.  VEHICLE #1 SUSTAINED MAJOR ROLLOVER TRAFFIC COLLISION DAMAGE TO ITS TRUCK CAB AND MODERATE ROLLOVER DAMAGE TO ITS CARGO TANK TRAILER.  VEHICLE #1 WAS LIFTED BY THOMPSON & RICH CRANE SERVICE, INC. AND TOWED FROM THE TRAFFIC COLLISION SCENE BY KESSLER'S TOWING TO THEIR YARD.  VEHICLE #1 WAS INSPECTED BY CALIFORNIA HIGHWAY PATROL COMMERCIAL OFFICER G.L. PRITCHET #7237, ON JANUARY 29, 2001 AT 1400 HOURS.  REFER TO THE ATTACHED VEHICLE INSPECTION REPORT. PHYSICAL EVIDENCE: TIRE MARK INDENTATION - REFER TO FACTUAL DIAGRAM. CENTRIFUGAL SKID MARK - REFER TO FACTUAL DIAGRAM. WHITE PAINT TRANSFER - REFER TO FACTUAL DIAGRAM. DIRT GOUGE MARK - REFER TO FACTUAL DIAGRAM. HAZARDOUS MATERIALS: VEHICLE #1'S CARGO TANK WAS LOADED WITH APPROXIMATELY 9,450 GALLONS OF "LPG" (LIQUID PROPANE GAS).  THE CARGO TANK RUPTURED UPON IMPACT WITH ASPHALT ROADWAY AND THE MAJORITY OF THE LOAD SPILLED OUT ONTO THE WEST SHOULDER OF THE ROAD AND INTO THE ATMOSPHERE.  VEHICLE #1 HAD THE PROPER PLACARDS, LABELS, AND SHIPPING PAPERS, DESCRIBING THE LOAD. HAZARDOUS MATERIALS: EL DORADO COUNTY ENVIRONMENTAL MANAGEMENT DEPARTMENT RESPONDED TO THE SCENE TO COORDINATE AND PERFORM CLEAN-UP OPERATIONS.  THE CLEAN-UP OPERATIONS WERE COMPLETED AND SCENE

MR. GARY HARTWIG CONTACTED MR. KENDEL KRUSE OF CONTRACT FREIGHTERS, INC. (C.F.I.) CONCERNING PRODUCT COMING FORM THE FRONT OF HIS TRAILER. MR. HARTWIG STATED HE COULD SMELL ACID FUMES. MR. HARTWIG STATED HE DIDN'T KNOW HOW MUCH WAS LEAKING. MR. HARTWIG WAS INSTRUCTED TO MOVE THE TRACTOR/TRAILER TO A SECURE LOCATION. MR. HARTWIG WAS INFORMED TO KEEP THE GENERAL PUBLIC AWAY FORM THE TRAILER UNTIL A RESPONSE TEAM ARRIVED. MR. KRUSE REQUESTED ALL STATE OFFICIALS BE CONTACTED. MR. TUCKER CONTACTED EP&S TO REQUEST ASSISTANCE TO A SPILL. THE TEAM ARRIVED ON SITE & DISCOVERED A 25X4 FT AREA OF ASPHALT CONTAMINATED WITH ACID. SODA ASH & ABSORBENT WERE USED TO NEUTRALIZE THE ACID. THE TRACTOR WAS DISCONNECTED FROM THE TRAILER. THE OUTSIDE AREA WAS SECURED. THE TEAM ENTERED THE TRAILER. A DRUM OF SULFURIC ACID WAS DISCOVERED LEAKING IN THE FRONT OF THE TRAILER. THE DRUM WAS PLACED INTO AN OVERPACK. THE ASPHALT AROUND THE TRAILER WAS CLEANED. THE INSIDE OF THE TRAILER WAS CLEANED. A SECOND TRAILER ARRIVED ON SITE FOR TRANSPORTING. STATE OFFICIAL REQUIRED THE FLOOR OF THE CONTAMINATED TRAILER TO BE REMOVED. THE FRONT 1/4 OF THE TRAILER'S FLOOR WAS REMOVED. THE FIRST TRAILER WAS DECONNED & ALL WASTE WAS PLACED INTO 55-GALLON DRUM. AN OVERPACK, PALLET OF HCL AND WASTE DRUMS WERE TRANSPORTED TO ENVIRONMENTAL PRODUCTS. THE WASTE WILL BE SENT TO CYCLE CHEM FOR DISPOSAL. ARRANGEMENTS ARE CURRENTLY BEING MADE TO TRANSPORT THE PALLET OF HCL TO THE SHIPPER

column42: GASOLINE INCLUDES GASOLINE MIXED WITH ETHYL ALCOHOL, WITH NOT MORE THAN 10% ALCOHOL
column168: ON MONDAY 01/22/01, AN ORDER FOR 3,000 GASOLINE WAS PLACED.  THE FUEL SUPPLY COMPANY WAS SERVICE ENERGY LLC.  OUR LOCAL REP/BROKER WAS ON VACATION. THEREFORE, THE CALL WAS PLACED TO THEIR OFFICE IN DELAWARE TO MIKE STEINER.  ON TUESDAY, 01/23/01 AT APPROXIMATELY 2:30 PM, IT WAS NOTICED THAT THE DELIVERY HAD NOT YET ARRIVED.  OUR PROCUREMENT CLERK (RITA BELT) CALLED SERVICE ENERGY TO FIND OUT WHERE THE DELIVERY WAS.  AFTER SEVERAL PHONE CONVERSATIONS BETWEEN MRS BELT AND MR STEINER, SHE WAS ASSURED THAT THE DELIVER WOULD ARRIVE SHORTLY.  THE FIRST FUEL DELIVERY ARRIVED AT USG AT APPROXIMATELY 3:30 PM AND OFF LOADED 3,099 GALLONS.  A SECOND TRUCK CARRYING 3,000 GALLONS THEN ARRIVED AT APPROXIMATELY 5:30 PM NOT KNOWING THERE WAS A FIRST TRUCK.  BOTH TRUCKS WERE DISPATCHED THROUGH SERVICE ENERGY.  THE OPERATOR OF THE SECOND TRUCK, CHECKED THE GARAGE WHICH WAS BROKEN (DISPLAYING A LOWER LEVEL THAN WHAT ACTUALLY WAS IN TANK) THEN PROCEEDED TO OFF-LOAD. HE OFFLOADED FOR APPROXIMATELY 10 MINUTES BEFORE NOTICING THERE WAS GASOLINE COMING OUT OF THE VAPOR RECOVERY HOSE.  HE THEN SHUT DOWN OPERATIONS.  THE OPERATOR STATES HE THEN CALLED HIS SUPERVISOR NOTIFYING HIM OF THE INCIDENT, AND ALSO TOLD SOMEONE IN THE USG BREAKROOM. PLACED APPROXIMATELY 20 BOOMS (SMALL, APPROX. 3" DIA X 2 FT LONG) IN FRONT OF SPILL.  SPILL WAS SUCCESSFULLY CONTAINED NOT ENTERING WATERS OF THE STATE.  CALLED CLEAN HARBORS TO BEGIN REMOVED AFTER OUR MECHANICS REPORTED SPILL WAS MORE THAN 50-75 GALLONS;  AS PREVIOUSLY ESTIMATED.  CLEAN HARBORS ARRIVED SOON AFTER MDE.  THEY COLLABORATED ON CLEAN-UP PROCEDURES.  SPILL WAS REMOVED (GAS/WATER MIXTURE) ON 01/24/01.  CLEAN HARBORS ARRIVED AT APPROX. 8:00 AM AS 01/25/01 TO REMOVE SOIL.
